{
  "texts": [
    "Training set attack defenses detect and mitigate poisoning and backdoor attacks (Li et al., 2022).",
    "Since malicious training instances must be influential to achieve the attacker's objective, defending against adversarial attacks reduces to identifying abnormally influential training instances.",
    "If attackers are constrained in the number of training instances they can insert (Wallace et al., 2021; You et al., 2023), the target of a training set attack can be identified by searching for test instances that have a few exceptionally influential training instances (Hammoudeh & Lowd, 2022).",
    "The training set attack mitigation removes these anomalously influential instances from the training data and then retrains the model (Wang et al., 2019).",
    "In addition, influence estimation has been applied to the related task of evasion attack detection, where the training set is pristine and only test instances are perturbed (Cohen et al., 2020)."
  ]
}